x11 passwd set
=============
x11vnc -storepasswd
// stores the passwd at ~/.vnc/passwd

alias x11='sudo /usr/bin/x11vnc -xkb -auth /var/run/lightdm/root/:0 -noxrecord
-noxfixes -noxdamage -rfbauth ~/.vnc/passwd -forever -bg -rfbport 5900 -o /var/log/x11vnc.log'

SSH setup:
==========

-> apt-get -y install openssh-servere
-> edit/check /etc/ssh/sshd_config
-> restart ssh

-> to setup ssh without passwd
    cat ~/.ssh/id_rsa.pub | ssh spitchai@10.33<IP> "cat >> ~/.ssh/authorized_keys"


To setup static IP:
===================

/* to configure static IP for ubuntu */

@ file /etc/network/interface

root@prmh-edge-ivybridge-09:/etc/network# cat /etc/network/interfaces
# This file describes the network interfaces available on your system
# and how to activate them. For more information, see interfaces(5).

# The loopback network interface
auto lo
iface lo inet loopback

# The primary network interface
# This is an autoconfigured IPv6 interface
auto em3
iface em3 inet static
address 10.24.235.88
netmask 255.255.252.0
gateway 10.24.235.253
dns-nameservers 10.20.30.1 10.20.30.2
dns-search eng.vmware.com
root@prmh-edge-ivybridge-09:/etc/network#

NFS:
===
apt-get install nfs-kernel-server

Setting up coredump:
====================
sudo apt-get install linux-crashdump

File system:
============
see the files mounted

/proc/mounts

/etc/mtab       mount and unmount command uses /etc/mtab.

/etc/fstab      contains a list of filesystems that are supposed to get
                mounted automatically when the system starts up.

df -ah          // {a} all and {h} human
du -sh          // {s} summary {h} human readable
fdisk -l        // list the disk partition table

Source code for ubuntu:
=======================

apt-get source linux-image-$(uname -r)

git clone https://github.com/torvalds/linux.git


Sharing folder with as VM:
=========================

-> check /mnt/hgfs that you can access your shared folder.

    If you don't see your shared folders (automounted) inside /mnt/hgfs , run VMware configuration tools:

    sudo vmware-config-tools.pl

-> update your fstab using the details below:

    edit /etc/fstab

    .host:/{shared-folder} /{path-to-mount-on} vmhgfs defaults,ttl=5,uid=1000,gid=1000   0 0

-> Restart your vm
